  "prompt": "What is the best code troll you've ever seen?",
  "response": "Coding pranks and trolls can range from humorous to frustrating. Here are a few classic and lighthearted examples:\n\n### 1. Naming Variables\n```python\n# Naming variables to confuse anyone reading the code\na = b\nb = c\nc = a + b\n```\n### 2. Commenting Nonexistent Features\n```python\n# This function performs advanced AI computations\n\ndef foo():\n    return 42\n```\n\n### 3. Unreadable Code\n```python\ndef _():__=lambda _,__:_.get(__);____=__({True.__name__:[[]]},\"__repr__\").__call__.__self__;(____+[*____])[0][0]=print\n_()(____)[0][0]( \"Easter Egg\" )\n```\n\n### 4. Overly Complicated One-Liners\n```python\n# Writing simple assignments in overly complicated ways\nresult = (lambda x: x + sum([i for i in range(10)]))(5)\n```\n\n### 5. Self-Destructing Code\n```python\nimport os\n# Deletes all files in the directory when run (don't actually run this)\nos.system(\"rm -rf *\")\n```\n(Note: This is very harmful and should never be used.)\n\n### 6. Endless Recursion\n```python\n# Creates an infinite loop \ndef infinite():\n    return infinite()\n\ninfinite()\n```\n\nThe best trolls are those that are good-natured and don\u2019t cause real harm or frustration to the developers involved. Always ensure that pranks remain within the realm of humor and do not interfere with the productivity or well-being of others.",
